<p><sup><a href="#_ftnref26" name="_ftn26">26</a> </sup>It is fanciful for an historian to imagine, as Prof. Andrews evidently does, that the Second World War was driven, even ostensibly, by a desire to end racism. Certainly, the British were committed to ending atrocities being perpetrated on the grounds of race, in Germany as in any country or colony, but “racism” in its modern-day conception was simply not recognised at the time. It is therefore unclear to what event Prof. Andrews is alluding when he claims that “we declared the end of racism” following the Allied victory.</p>
<p><sup><a href="#_ftnref27" name="_ftn27">27</a> </sup>Paul, Addison, “Keeping the Record Accurate: Churchill and the Sterilisation Issue,” <em>Finest Hour</em> 131, Summer 2006, 22</p>
<p><sup><a href="#_ftnref28" name="_ftn28">28</a> </sup>Richard M. Langworth, “Churchill’s ‘Aryan Stock’ Quotation: Principles, Facts and Heresies,” 30 November 2020. <a href="https://richardlangworth.com/aryan-stock" onclick="__gaTracker('send', 'event', 'outbound-article', 'https://richardlangworth.com/aryan-stock', 'Online');">Online</a>.</p>
